Part 1: Regression analysis of Gapminder data

Exercise 1: Make a scatter plot of life expectancy across time.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title="Life expectancy over time",
         x = "year",
         y = "life expectancy")

Question 1: Is there a general trend (e.g., increasing or decreasing) for life expectancy across time? Is this trend linear?

There is a generally increasing trend for life expectancy across time and it appears to follow a straight line so it may be linear.

A slightly different way of making the same plot is looking at the distribution of life expectancy across countries as it changes over time:

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=lifeExp)) +
    geom_violin() +
    labs(title="Life expectancy over time",
         x = "year",
         y = "life expectancy")

Question 2: How would you describe the distribution of life expectancy across countries for individual years? Is it skewed, or not? Unimodal or not? Symmetric around its center?

The peak of life expectancy goes from bottom to top across time. In 1952, the peak shows at the bottom. As time goes on, the peak gets closer to the top. By 2007, the data is mostly concentrated around the top. Also, while the spread span stays roughly the same, the distribution is moving to higher figures. The general shape of the distribution (skinny on one end and wide in the other) indicates the distribution of life expectancy is skewed. The distribution appears to be multimodal before 1977 and unimodal after. None of the violins looks symmetric hence the distribution is not symmetric around the center.

Question 3: Suppose I fit a linear regression model of life expectancy vs. year (treating it as a continuous variable), and test for a relationship between year and life expectancy, will you reject the null hypothesis of no relationship? (do this without fitting the model yet. I am testing your intuition.)

It looks like there exists a linear relationship between year and life expectancy. So I would reject the null hypothesis of no relationship.

Question 4: What would a violin plot of residuals from the linear model in Question 3 vs. year look like? (Again, don’t do the analysis yet, answer this intuitively)

I would also expect the residual graph to follow a linear pattern since I believe there exists a linear relationship between year and life expectancy.

Question 5: According to the assumptions of the linear regression model, what should that violin plot look like?

The violins should look roughly symmetrical with one peak in the middle and very similar to one another in shape and size. Their peaks are generally around 0. Also, they should roughly follow a linear pattern.

Exercise 2: Fit a linear regression model using the lm function for life expectancy vs. year (as a continuous variable). Use the broom::tidy to look at the resulting model.

fit <- lm(lifeExp~year, data = gapminder)
fit_stats <- fit %>%
  broom::tidy()
fit_stats
##          term     estimate   std.error statistic      p.value
## 1 (Intercept) -585.6521874 32.31396452 -18.12381 2.897807e-67
## 2        year    0.3259038  0.01632369  19.96509 7.546795e-80

Question 6: On average, by how much does life expectancy increase every year around the world?

On average, life expectancy increases by 0.33 year every year around the world.

Question 7: Do you reject the null hypothesis of no relationship between year and life expectancy? Why?

We reject the null hypothesis because the p-value (7.546795e-80) is essentially zero (<0.05).

Exercise 3: Make a violin plot of residuals vs. year for the linear model from Exercise 2 (use the broom::augment function).

fit %>%
  augment(data=gapminder) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=.resid)) +
  geom_violin() +
  labs(title="Residual vs. Year",
         x = "year",
         y = "residual")

Question 8: Does the plot of Exercise 3 match your expectations (as you answered Question 4)?

Yes. The pattern does look linear.

Exercise 4: Make a boxplot (or violin plot) of model residuals vs. continent.

fit %>%
  augment(data=gapminder) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=continent, y=.resid)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title="Residual vs. Continent",
       x = "continent",
       y = "residual")

Question 9: Is there a dependence between model residual and continent? If so, what would that suggest when performing a regression analysis of life expectancy across time?

In our boxplot above, we can see that the distribution of model residual (mean and variance) varies from continent to continent, which suggests a dependency between model residual and continent. This indicates that our model perhaps did not capture all the variables that would affect life expectancy.

Exercise 5: Use geom_smooth(method=lm) in ggplot as part of a scatter plot of life expectancy vs. year, grouped by continent (e.g., using the color aesthetic mapping).

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=lifeExp, group=continent, color=continent)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  labs(title="Life expectancy over time grouped by continent",
         x = "year",
         y = "life expectancy")

Question 10: Based on this plot, should your regression model include an interaction term for continent and year? Why?

In the plot above, the fitted linear models vary from continent to continent (not parallel). Hence, the regression model should include an interaction term for continent and year.

Exercise 6: Fit a linear regression model for life expectancy including a term for an interaction between continent and year. Use the broom::tidy function to show the resulting model.

multi_fit <- lm(lifeExp~year*continent, data=gapminder)

Exercise 7: Use the anova function to perform an F-test that compares how well two models fit your data: (a) the linear regression models from Exercise 2 (only including year as a covariate) and (b) Exercise 6 (including interaction between year and continent).

We use the anova() function, which performs an F-test in order to test the null hypothesis that a model M1 is sufficient to explain the data against the alternative hypothesis that a more complex model M2 is required.

Question 13: Is the interaction model significantly better than the year-only model? Why?

The p-value comparing the year-only model to the interaction model is essentially zero (\(<10^{-15}\)), indicating that the first model is not sufficient. Also, there is a big drop in RSS (230229 to 87320). Hence the interaction model is significantly better than the year-only model.

Exercise 8: Make a residuals vs. year violin plot for the interaction model. Comment on how well it matches assumptions of the linear regression model. Do the same for a residuals vs. fitted values model. (You should use the broom::augment function).

This residuals vs. year violin plot shows that (1) they’re pretty symmetrically distributed, tending to cluster towards the middle of the plot; (2) they’re clustered around 0 of the y-axis; (3) in general there aren’t clear patterns. All of these qualities suggest that the interaction model performs reasonably well.

multi_fit %>%
  augment(data=gapminder) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=.resid)) +
  geom_violin() +
  labs(title="Residual vs. Year",
       x = "year",
       y = "residual")

In the Residual vs. Fitted plot below, the residuals are not perfectly random. However, it does not show obvious bias and centered around 0. Hence, I think the performance of the interaction model is acceptable.

multi_fit %>%
  augment(data=gapminder) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=.fitted, y=.resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title="Residual vs. Fitted",
     x = "fitted value",
     y = "residual")

Part 2: Classification

1. Code to prepare data

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
theme_set(theme_bw())

csv_file <- "Affordability_Wide_2017Q4_Public.csv"
tidy_afford <- read_csv(csv_file) %>%
  filter(Index == "Mortgage Affordability") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  filter(RegionID != 0, RegionName != "United States") %>%
  dplyr::select(RegionID, RegionName, matches("^[1|2]")) %>%
  gather(time, affordability, matches("^[1|2]")) %>%
  type_convert(col_types=cols(time=col_date(format="%Y-%m")))

outcome_df <- tidy_afford %>%
  mutate(yq = quarter(time, with_year=TRUE)) %>%
  filter(yq %in% c("2016.4", "2017.4")) %>%
  select(RegionID, RegionName, yq, affordability) %>%
  spread(yq, affordability) %>%
  mutate(diff = `2017.4` - `2016.4`) %>%
  mutate(Direction = ifelse(diff>0, "up", "down")) %>%
  select(RegionID, RegionName, Direction)

2. Discussion of the question you have chosen to address including discussion of other choices you have made (e.g., feature representation, classification algorithm) to carry out your experiment.

The question I want to address is: Is a random forest better than a decision tree? To carry out the experiment, we need a table with one row per region, and attributes corresponding to differences in quarterly affordability. I will use data since 2000 because we can see that the variance becomes larger than before on the data plot. Also, I will standardize affordability for each region to reduce the noise.

3. Code to carry out your cross-validation experiment.

  1. Prepare data for training

First, filter to the years of interest and standardize affordability for each region:

standardized_df <- predictor_df %>%
  filter(year(time) %in% 2000:2016) %>%
  group_by(RegionID) %>%
  mutate(mean_aff = mean(affordability)) %>%
  mutate(sd_aff = sd(affordability)) %>%
  mutate(z_aff = (affordability - mean_aff) / sd_aff) %>%
  ungroup()

  1. Cross Vatidation Carry out 10-fold cross validation and keep track of the result for each model:
library(ROCR)
library(cvTools)

fold_indices <- cvFolds(nrow(sample_frac(final_df, 1)), K=10, type = "consecutive")

cv_result <- sapply(1:10, function(fold_index) {
  test_indices <- which(fold_indices$which == fold_index)
  test_set <- final_df[test_indices,]
  train_set <- final_df[-test_indices,]
  
  tree_fit <- tree::tree(Direction~., data=train_set %>% select(-RegionID))
  tree_pred <- predict(tree_fit, newdata=test_set %>% select(-RegionID), type="class")
  tree_error <- mean(test_set$Direction != tree_pred)
  
  rf_fit <- randomForest::randomForest(Direction~., data=train_set %>% select(-RegionID))
  rf_pred <- predict(rf_fit, newdata=test_set %>% select(-RegionID))
  rf_error <- mean(test_set$Direction != rf_pred)
  
  tree_pred_prob <- predict(tree_fit, newdata=test_set %>% select(-RegionID), type="vector")[,2]
  rf_pred_prob <- predict(rf_fit, newdata=test_set %>% select(-RegionID), type = "prob")[,2]
  c(tree_error, rf_error, tree_pred_prob, rf_pred_prob, test_set$Direction)
})

Draw the AUROC curve plot for Decision Tree and compute the average AUROC:

pred <- prediction(tree_pred, test_label)
perf <- performance(pred,"tpr","fpr")
auc <- mean(unlist(performance(pred, "auc")@y.values))
plot(perf, colorize=T, lty=2.5, main = paste("Average Decision Tree AUROC", round(auc,2)))

plot(perf,lwd=1,avg="vertical",spread.estimate="boxplot",add=TRUE)

Draw the AUROC curve plot for Random Forest and compute the average AUROC:

plot(perf, colorize=T, lty=2.5, main = paste("Average Random Forest AUROC", round(auc,2)))

5. Interpretation and discussion of your experiment results.
I tend to believe that the random forest tree performs better based on the AUROC curves above because the it has a higher AUROC. However, we can not reject the null hypothesis because the p-value we got from the t-test is too high (>0.05). Hence in this case we do not observe significant difference between these two models.
